@article{Baller2001a,
abstract = {This study applies recently developed techniques of spatial analysis to explain intercounty variation in homicide rates at four time points between 1960 and 1990. The data for the homicide rates were constructed for U.S. counties (N = 3,085) from the National Center for Health Statistics mortality files and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention WONDER system. A combination of exploratory spatial data analysis and spatial economic techniques, including Moran's I statistic (Cliff {\&} Ord, 1981), were used. Homicide is not randomly distributed in space. Throughout the 1960 to 1990 period, county-level homicide rates exhibited appreciable positive spatial autocorrelation. Furthermore, a distinctive regional imprint for this spatial autocorrelation emerged. Counties in the South had higher than average homicide rates than those from statistically significant clusters. The South and the non-South constitute two distinct spatial regimes in the geographic clustering of homicide. Spatial clustering was also found to persist even after controlling for the widely recognized structural predictors of homicide, suggesting that homicide rates are not generated solely by internal structural factors. Significant regional differences in the effects of structural predictors were also found. Homicide researchers should attend to these patterns of spatial distribution to estimate the effects of nonspatial variables, and to identify potential sites for substantively interesting processes, such as diffusion. The application of spatial econometrics offers promising opportunities for expanding our understanding of how social forces contribute to interpersonal violence.},
